The mockups look "finished" because the design is clean, but they're actually hiding behind emojis and gradient backgrounds where real photography should be doing the heavy lifting. A food wholesaler without food photography is like a restaurant with no menu photos — it kills trust.
Let me map out every image placement across both pages, what each image should be, and why it matters.
Food Service page — 11 image placements:

Hero background/image (the big placeholder box, right side) — This is the most important image on the entire site. Should be a real photo of either a busy commercial kitchen with Indus Foods branded products visible, or a delivery driver handing boxes to a restaurant owner. NOT a stock photo of generic spices.
8 product category tiles (Spices, Rice, Lentils, etc.) — Currently using emojis. Each needs a real product photo showing the actual packaging in catering sizes. A 10kg bag of Sanam spices is more convincing than a chilli emoji. These should be shot on a clean background, consistent style across all 8.
Delivery coverage map (the dark section placeholder) — An actual styled map of the UK showing delivery zones, or at minimum a photo of the Indus Foods delivery fleet/warehouse.
3 testimonial avatars — Currently using initials in circles. Real headshots of actual customers would be ideal, but if customers won't provide photos, the initials approach is fine. Don't use stock headshots — people can tell.
Certification logos — Currently text boxes saying "BRC Certified" etc. These need the actual logo images for each certification.
Logo in header — Currently "IF" in a gold box. Needs the real Indus Foods logo.

Trade Application page — 4 image placements:

Logo — Same as above, real logo.
8 product category tiles in Step 3 — Same product photography as the food service page, just smaller. Consistency matters.
Certification badges in sidebar — Same real logos.
